Wrap the outputStream in try-with-resources and use try-with-resources for the ParquetWriter as well:
  try (OutputStream outputStream = outputFile.create();
       ParquetWriter parquetWriter = new ParquetWriter(outputStream, ...)) {
      parquetWriter.write(...);
  }
Then read fileMetaData and estimatedWrittenBytes after the try block (both are safe after close()).

Build a NavigableMap<Long, DataFileRange> (keyed by rowIdStart) once in the constructor, then use floorEntry(rowId) to resolve in O(log F):
  private final NavigableMap<Long, DataFileRange> rangeByRowIdStart =
      new TreeMap<>();
  // in constructor: mergeHandle.dataFileRanges().forEach(r -> rangeByRowIdStart.put(r.rowIdStart(), r));
  // in resolve: Map.Entry<Long,DataFileRange> e = rangeByRowIdStart.floorEntry(rowId);
  // check e != null && e.getValue().containsRowId(rowId).

Replace the round-trip with a direct add:
  fragments.add(insertFragment);
The bytes are already in the correct DucklakeWriteFragment JSON format. If a type tag is needed to distinguish delete vs. insert fragments in finishMerge, the distinction is better made structurally (e.g. a wrapper record) rather than a redundant re-encode.
